One final question, and
kind of a personal one,

01:01:29.092 --> 01:01:31.595
are there some mountains out
there still for Rod Canton

01:01:31.887 --> 01:01:33.230
to climb?

01:01:33.513 --> 01:01:36.141
I think my biggest challenge
for the foreseeable future

01:01:36.433 --> 01:01:38.561
is to keep Compaq together.

01:01:38.852 --> 01:01:41.776
Keep the culture,
keep it rolling,

01:01:42.063 --> 01:01:43.531
and reach whatever
potential's there.

01:01:43.815 --> 01:01:46.659
Nobody really knows how fast and
how far a computer company can

01:01:46.943 --> 01:01:48.103
go, and I'd like to see that.

01:01:48.361 --> 01:01:50.363
Compaq Computer is one
of the fastest growing

01:01:50.655 --> 01:01:52.077
personal computer makers.

01:01:52.365 --> 01:01:54.868
There's a company whose sales
have grown from $111 million

01:01:55.160 --> 01:01:58.664
in 1983 to more than
$2 billion last year.

01:01:58.955 --> 01:02:00.127
So what's to worry about?

01:02:00.415 --> 01:02:03.635
It was a very different company.

01:02:03.919 --> 01:02:05.887
How do you manage 17,000
people in the same way

01:02:06.171 --> 01:02:07.815
that you manage a hundred...
It's not possible.

01:02:07.839 --> 01:02:11.594
Every time you
hire you end up, potentially,

01:02:11.885 --> 01:02:14.434
starting to dilute,
and then over time you

01:02:14.721 --> 01:02:17.144
end up with an
organization that isn't

01:02:17.432 --> 01:02:19.400
the same as the organization
you started with.

01:02:19.684 --> 01:02:21.324
Has the fun gone out
of it now that you've

01:02:21.436 --> 01:02:22.636
built this successful company?

01:02:22.812 --> 01:02:23.313
Will you stay with it?

01:02:23.605 --> 01:02:24.652
What are your plans?

01:02:24.940 --> 01:02:26.692
Oh, no, the fun is still there.

01:02:26.983 --> 01:02:30.533
The challenge is different,
that's all I can say.

01:02:30.820 --> 01:02:32.580
There's nothing quite
like starting a company

01:02:32.739 --> 01:02:34.366
and having it grow rapidly.

01:02:34.658 --> 01:02:37.502
As we moved to a
Fortune 500 status

01:02:37.786 --> 01:02:39.709
and then approaching the
billion dollar level,

01:02:39.996 --> 01:02:42.465
the problems are different.

01:02:42.749 --> 01:02:44.296
We knew we needed a leader

01:02:44.584 --> 01:02:49.306
to build a team in Europe,
and through a recommendation,

01:02:49.589 --> 01:02:51.683
we contacted Eckhard
Pfeiffer and very

01:02:51.967 --> 01:02:53.402
quickly he joined
the company and began

01:02:53.426 --> 01:02:54.643
to build our European team.

01:02:54.928 --> 01:02:57.681
We decided that we would
go into the major markets

01:02:57.973 --> 01:03:02.069
right from the start, which were
Germany, the UK, and France.

01:03:02.352 --> 01:03:03.774
And from then on
expand gradually

01:03:04.062 --> 01:03:05.860
into all the other countries.

01:03:06.147 --> 01:03:11.244
He was more accustomed to
high volume manufacturing,

01:03:11.528 --> 01:03:16.079
get the cost out,
kinds of situations

01:03:16.366 --> 01:03:19.540
and that's exactly what Compaq
needed with the new lower

01:03:19.828 --> 01:03:20.920
cost product line.

01:03:21.204 --> 01:03:22.844
In our CEO forum this
week, we take a look

01:03:23.123 --> 01:03:25.751
at the art of competing on
the international scene.

01:03:26.042 --> 01:03:28.170
American companies
versus the Japanese.

01:03:28.461 --> 01:03:30.634
Do you worry about
the competition that's

01:03:30.922 --> 01:03:32.799
coming from the Far
East and from Europe,

01:03:33.091 --> 01:03:34.571
particularly in the
computer industry?

01:03:34.676 --> 01:03:37.099
The Japanese certainly
have a lot of strengths.

01:03:37.387 --> 01:03:40.231
The Japanese company has major
competitors in the long term.

01:03:40.515 --> 01:03:42.609
Foreign manufacturers
got to be pretty good.

01:03:42.892 --> 01:03:46.317
Quality improved, and
essentially, for someone

01:03:46.604 --> 01:03:50.029
like Compaq, they no
longer could get that price

01:03:50.316 --> 01:03:51.909
advantage that they once had.

01:03:52.193 --> 01:03:55.367
You wouldn't want to buy these
things for $3,000 anymore.

01:03:55.655 --> 01:03:57.407
Could you buy them for $1,000?

01:03:57.699 --> 01:03:59.076
Do I hear $950?

01:03:59.367 --> 01:04:01.995
The new notebooks
like Toshiba's T-1000,

01:04:02.287 --> 01:04:05.461
Tandy's 1,100-FD and
Zenus Mini Sport are

01:04:05.749 --> 01:04:07.672
in the $1,000 to $2,000 range.

01:04:07.959 --> 01:04:13.090
At the high end, about
$4,000, Compaq LTE 286.

01:04:13.381 --> 01:04:15.383
We had companies like
Dell Computer actually

01:04:15.675 --> 01:04:18.098
begin to build better
and better products,

01:04:18.386 --> 01:04:20.354
and they were selling
them at a lower price.

01:04:20.638 --> 01:04:22.265
Compaq, the Houston giant,

01:04:22.557 --> 01:04:24.597
has been facing an advertising
assault from the much

01:04:24.851 --> 01:04:26.273
smaller Dell Computer.

01:04:26.561 --> 01:04:29.531
The industry can't recall
anything like these biting ads

01:04:29.814 --> 01:04:31.612
comparing features and price.

01:04:31.900 --> 01:04:36.076
The Dell ad calls Dell
appealing and Compaq appalling.

01:04:36.362 --> 01:04:37.830
Dell, top of the mark.

01:04:38.114 --> 01:04:40.333
Compaq, top of the mark-ups.

01:04:40.617 --> 01:04:42.585
Compaq is not amused.

01:04:42.869 --> 01:04:46.089
You can't survive, I believe,
for very long at least,

01:04:46.372 --> 01:04:48.372
just by selling the same
products at a lower price.

01:04:48.458 --> 01:04:49.835
And there were people

01:04:50.126 --> 01:04:52.424
who said we need to get a low
cost product out there now

01:04:52.712 --> 01:04:55.807
and take on these people.

01:04:56.091 --> 01:04:58.264
That was primarily
led by Pfeiffer.

01:05:01.846 --> 01:05:03.286
I think it has been
a little bit more

01:05:03.515 --> 01:05:07.110
difficult for them to
keep up with the changing

01:05:07.393 --> 01:05:08.485
in technology.

01:05:08.770 --> 01:05:10.331
Compaq, a darling of Wall Street

01:05:10.355 --> 01:05:12.278
that could do little
wrong in the past,

01:05:12.565 --> 01:05:15.068
found itself on the
market's bad side last week,

01:05:15.360 --> 01:05:16.782
Compaq's stock plunged.

01:05:17.070 --> 01:05:19.744
On paper, combined
losses to all shareholders

01:05:20.031 --> 01:05:22.409
of more than $740 million.

01:05:22.700 --> 01:05:25.954
It certainly is a stumble in
the eyes of the stockholders.

01:05:26.246 --> 01:05:31.548
We didn't want to disappoint
relative to expectations,

01:05:31.835 --> 01:05:33.270
but I think you've got
to differentiate that

01:05:33.294 --> 01:05:34.796
from the actual
health of the company.

01:05:35.088 --> 01:05:39.264
Ben, with some
prodding from Pfeiffer,

01:05:39.551 --> 01:05:42.930
was becoming paranoid that we
would not be able to recognize,

01:05:43.221 --> 01:05:46.896
and switch, and move, from as
high a quality provider as we

01:05:47.183 --> 01:05:50.562
were to low cost computers.

01:05:50.854 --> 01:05:52.731
We certainly
started seeing changes

01:05:53.022 --> 01:05:59.155
in marketing strategies,
changes in the competitor base,

01:05:59.445 --> 01:06:02.119
changes in the
importance of pricing.

01:06:02.407 --> 01:06:04.375
The essential view
was that Rod could not

01:06:04.659 --> 01:06:07.378
adapt to what the company
needed going forward.

01:06:07.662 --> 01:06:09.039
Ben had other concerns about it.

01:06:09.330 --> 01:06:15.463
He was more concerned
about me losing

01:06:15.753 --> 01:06:16.793
commitment to the company.

01:06:17.046 --> 01:06:20.892
Rod was working on
a low cost concept,

01:06:21.176 --> 01:06:27.104
but I don't think he was pushing
it enough to satisfy the board.

01:06:27.390 --> 01:06:29.734
The chairman of your company
is a guy named Ben Rosen.

01:06:30.018 --> 01:06:33.318
What's the chemistry
between the two of you?

01:06:33.605 --> 01:06:35.323
I'd say Ben and I
are very good friends.

01:06:35.607 --> 01:06:39.328
Ben joined Compaq at a time
when we were just forming,

01:06:39.611 --> 01:06:41.409
and I think he's played
a key role in helping

01:06:41.696 --> 01:06:43.414
guide us along the way.

01:06:43.698 --> 01:06:45.458
We have a lot of mutual
respect, and we bring

01:06:45.575 --> 01:06:48.454
different things to the party.

01:06:48.745 --> 01:06:50.848
You have to
give Ben credit for two things.

01:06:50.872 --> 01:06:53.091
One, he saw that the
vision was a real vision.

01:06:53.374 --> 01:06:57.254
He got it right away because
they did finance the plan,

01:06:57.545 --> 01:07:00.640
and then at each
stage thereafter

01:07:00.924 --> 01:07:04.394
he encouraged and supported.

01:07:04.677 --> 01:07:07.556
Without Ben Rosen Compaq
Computer Corporation

01:07:07.847 --> 01:07:09.087
would not be where it is today.

01:07:11.809 --> 01:07:13.857
The board did not want

01:07:14.145 --> 01:07:22.145
to take any action against
Rod, but they got to the point

01:07:24.030 --> 01:07:27.500
where they felt like
we had to do something.

01:07:48.721 --> 01:07:50.361
Ben decided that he might want

01:07:50.640 --> 01:07:52.000
to create a situation
where there's

01:07:52.183 --> 01:07:55.278
kind of two bosses,
Pfeiffer and Rod,

01:07:55.561 --> 01:08:01.034
because of a loss
of confidence in us.

01:08:01.317 --> 01:08:02.878
There are
some management changes

01:08:02.902 --> 01:08:05.997
that you make because an
opportunity is created

01:08:06.281 --> 01:08:10.127
by bringing that new person
in, and even at the time,

01:08:10.410 --> 01:08:14.790
there was no evidence
of that at Compaq.

01:08:15.081 --> 01:08:16.934
I don't
question the motives of it.

01:08:16.957 --> 01:08:21.087
I think Ben was
genuinely concerned,

01:08:21.379 --> 01:08:25.350
I mean there's just
no doubt about it.

01:08:25.633 --> 01:08:26.993
Rod wouldn't compromise

01:08:27.093 --> 01:08:28.560
and take the dual leadership.

01:08:31.930 --> 01:08:34.524
We were getting ready to have a
board meeting and Rod told me.

01:08:34.809 --> 01:08:36.607
He said, you know, Jim,
they're going to vote

01:08:36.894 --> 01:08:39.613
today on whether to remove me.

01:08:39.897 --> 01:08:41.569
My attitude when We
started Compaq was I

01:08:41.858 --> 01:08:45.078
would be ready to move aside
if that ever was necessary,

01:08:45.361 --> 01:08:46.921
and I thank the other
founders of Compaq

01:08:47.196 --> 01:08:49.698
had the same attitude.

01:08:49.991 --> 01:08:52.618
That night of the board meeting,

01:08:52.910 --> 01:08:58.462
it was 10:30, 11:00
o'clock at night.

01:08:58.750 --> 01:09:00.296
I got a call from Jim.

01:09:13.514 --> 01:09:14.783
I can only say there was

01:09:14.807 --> 01:09:16.184
open weeping in the hallways.

01:09:20.145 --> 01:09:22.386
Going on without
him was almost unimaginable.

01:09:27.069 --> 01:09:28.912
I had quit Compaq that day.

01:09:31.991 --> 01:09:33.426
It was like the heart and soul

01:09:33.451 --> 01:09:35.294
of the company being torn out.

01:09:38.456 --> 01:09:40.576
I went ahead and
turned my resignation in.

01:09:44.252 --> 01:09:47.381
I cannot even
think of being tired of what

01:09:47.673 --> 01:09:49.640
I'm doing and the
opportunity that I

01:09:49.926 --> 01:09:51.553
see at Compaq in
the same fault...

01:09:51.844 --> 01:09:53.029
They are two different things.

01:09:53.054 --> 01:09:55.773
I see so much
challenge out there,

01:09:56.057 --> 01:09:58.151
a challenge that, I
believe, we're capable of,

01:09:58.434 --> 01:10:00.311
and yet I really want
to see it through.

01:10:04.273 --> 01:10:06.073
Ben convinced himself that this

01:10:06.275 --> 01:10:07.401
was the right thing to make.

01:10:10.488 --> 01:10:11.740
He lost it.

01:10:12.031 --> 01:10:15.251
He said several tears
over the decision.

01:10:20.206 --> 01:10:24.131
It was inevitable
that there'd be a change.

01:10:34.303 --> 01:10:35.663
It was a very sad time.

01:10:40.351 --> 01:10:44.197
It sunk in, what had really
happened and what it meant.

01:10:47.608 --> 01:10:49.485
It took a very
long time before it

01:10:49.777 --> 01:10:53.532
finally began to feel normal
not to be there every clay.

01:10:53.823 --> 01:10:57.123
It was tough, it was tough
on... it was hard on me.

01:11:40.620 --> 01:11:42.873
Compaq's focus on portability

01:11:43.164 --> 01:11:45.041
was the beginning of
mobility and mattering

01:11:45.333 --> 01:11:53.333
to the technology industry,
and everything that we do today

01:11:53.966 --> 01:11:56.845
is really driven by
the ethic that if you

01:11:57.136 --> 01:12:00.731
can't do it While you're moving
around, it's not very valuable.

01:12:01.015 --> 01:12:03.313
And we can thank
Compaq for all of that.

01:12:03.601 --> 01:12:06.320
My dad would always look at
some of these cell phones,

01:12:06.604 --> 01:12:09.153
or some of the newer
computers, and say,

01:12:09.440 --> 01:12:11.943
are you responsible
for all of this stuff?

01:12:12.235 --> 01:12:13.435
Well, yeah, it's a good thing.

01:12:13.611 --> 01:12:15.488
I use iPhones, I use iPads, and I

01:12:15.780 --> 01:12:18.499
do know that if Compaq
developed those products... now,

01:12:18.783 --> 01:12:20.385
I'm not taking anything
away from those guys.

01:12:20.409 --> 01:12:22.471
Those guys did magnificent
job, and they can sell them

01:12:22.495 --> 01:12:26.625
to dead people, but if we
did them they'd work better,

01:12:26.916 --> 01:12:28.543
I know that.

01:12:28.834 --> 01:12:31.963
If anybody had tried to
tell me how successful.

01:12:32.255 --> 01:12:36.351
Compaq would become,
I would've just said,

01:12:36.634 --> 01:12:39.478
you're blowing smoke.

01:12:39.762 --> 01:12:40.763
That's not possible.

01:12:41.055 --> 01:12:45.310
We never, ever had
any idea that this

01:12:45.601 --> 01:12:49.105
would be as explosively
successful as it was, never.

01:12:49.397 --> 01:12:50.997
I don't think we were
ever trying to take

01:12:51.148 --> 01:12:54.197
down the biggest company, ever.

01:12:54.485 --> 01:12:56.408
We were trying to survive.

01:12:56.696 --> 01:13:01.372
Here was a product and
an idea for a start up

01:13:01.659 --> 01:13:05.084
that should have been in
Silicon Valley, if anywhere.

01:13:05.371 --> 01:13:05.963
But Houston?

01:13:06.247 --> 01:13:07.247
Give me a break.

01:13:07.498 --> 01:13:10.172
I had no idea we
were going to be doing

01:13:10.459 --> 01:13:11.562
a billion dollar
company... I mean,

01:13:11.586 --> 01:13:13.759
the billion dollar baby was IBM.

01:13:14.046 --> 01:13:16.720
How can I even conceive,
or think, that we

01:13:17.008 --> 01:13:20.763
would be an IBM in that sense?

01:13:21.053 --> 01:13:25.274
No way, not the slightest.

01:13:25.558 --> 01:13:28.732
I would still like to
have a Mexican restaurant.

